{"type":"text","timestamp":1773351989803,"sessionID":"ses_31c036c7affe6dPx3n8MQ9tKUs","part":{"id":"prt_ce403ca590027xyjvu94vhEX23","sessionID":"ses_31c036c7affe6dPx3n8MQ9tKUs","messageID":"msg_ce403c02a001yog5Vv6cFrtj0E","type":"text","text":"Now let me implement worktree reuse for sequential chains. When features A→B→C are in the same stream/chain, after A completes and is verified, B should reuse A's worktree. The key insight is:\n\n1. When creating agent entries for a chain, features 2..N in the chain should share the worktree path of the first feature\n2. After A completes and is verified/merged, B gets launched in the same worktree directory but with its own branch\n\nLet me think about this more carefully. The worktree is tied to a branch. So when we want to reuse a worktree for feature B after feature A is done, we need to:\n1. Keep the worktree (don't remove it after merge)\n2. Switch the worktree's branch from A's to B's\n3. This means we can't just assign the same path — we need to handle the branch switch\n\nActually, let me re-read the spec requirement: \"Sequential features in the same chain should reuse the same worktree.\" This makes sense for efficiency — avoid creating/destroying worktrees for each step in a chain. But the current system assigns each agent a unique worktree path.\n\nThe approach:\n1. In `cmdLaunch`, assign all agents in the same chain the same worktree path (the path of the first feature in the chain)\n2. When a chain-predecessor completes and is merged, DON'T remove the worktree — just let the next agent in the chain use it\n3. Modify `launchSingleHeadless` to handle chain worktree reuse: switch the branch in the worktree before launching the next agent\n4. Only remove the worktree when the last feature in the chain is done\n\nLet me implement this. First, I'll add worktree reuse logic to `launch.ts`:","time":{"start":1773351989802,"end":1773351989802}}}
